# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1993-world-trade-center-bombing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The original **One World Trade Center** (also known as the **North Tower**, **Tower 1**, **Building One**, or **1 WTC**) was one of the Twin Towers of the original World Trade Center complex in New York City.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] It started construction in 1968 and completed in 1972.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] It stood at a height of 1,368 feet (417.0 m), and was the tallest building in the world until 1973, when surpassed by the Sears Tower in Chicago.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] On the 106th and 107th floors of this building were a complex of dining, meeting, and entertainment venues known as Windows on the World.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] It was distinguishable from its twin, the original 2 World Trade Center, also known as the South Tower, by the 360-foot (110 m) telecommunications antenna on its roof.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Including the antenna, the building stood at a total height of 1,728 feet (526.7 m).
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The North Tower was 6 feet taller than the South Tower because floor 43 was 2 feet taller and floor 67 was 4 feet taller than the standard ceiling of 12 feet.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] These two floors were used by the Port Authority.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The building's address was **1 World Trade Center**, and the WTC complex had its own ZIP code (10048) due to its large size.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The original World Trade Center was destroyed in the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Struck by American Airlines Flight 11 at 8:46 a.m., the North Tower was the first of the Twin Towers to be hit by a hijacked aircraft, and the second to collapse, at 10:28 a.m.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The North Tower stood for 102 minutes after the aircraft impact.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Of the 2,996 people killed in the attacks, around 1,700 were in the North Tower or on the ground.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The North Tower was succeeded by the present-day One World Trade Center tower, which was opened in November 2014 as the lead building of the redeveloped World Trade Center site.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] At the National September 11 Memorial & Museum, the northern pool marks the spot where the North Tower once stood.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] In 1961, the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey agreed to build the World Trade Center on the site of the Hudson Terminal in Lower Manhattan, New York City.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] On September 20, 1962, the Port Authority announced the selection of Minoru Yamasaki as lead architect and Emery Roth & Sons as associate architects.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Yamasaki devised the plan to incorporate twin towers.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] His original plan called for the towers to be 80 stories tall, but to meet the Port Authority's requirement for 10,000,000 square feet (930,000 m2) of office space, the buildings would each have to be 110 stories tall.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Yamasaki's design for the World Trade Center, unveiled to the public on January 18, 1964, called for a square plan approximately 208 feet (63 m) in dimension on each side.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] In March 1965, the Port Authority began acquiring property at the World Trade Center site.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Demolition work began on March 21, 1966, and groundbreaking for the construction of the World Trade Center took place on August 5, 1966.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] In January 1967, the Port Authority awarded $74 million in contracts to various steel suppliers.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Construction work began on the North Tower in August 1968.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The topping out ceremony for 1 WTC (the North Tower) took place on December 23, 1970.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The first tenants moved into the North Tower on December 15, 1970, while it was still under construction, and a ribbon cutting ceremony took place on April 4, 1973.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] On February 12, 1975, a three-alarm fire broke out on the North Tower's 11th floor, spreading to the 9th and 14th floors.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] At that time, the World Trade Center had no fire sprinkler systems.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] A disgruntled custodian was discovered to have deliberately started the fire and was criminally charged.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Following the fire, in 1981, the Port Authority announced a $45 million plan to install sprinklers throughout the World Trade Center.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The first terrorist attack on the World Trade Center occurred on February 26, 1993, at 12:17 p.m.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] A Ryder truck filled with 1,500 pounds (680 kg) of explosives (planted by Ramzi Yousef) detonated in the North Tower's underground garage.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] According to a presiding judge, the conspirators' chief aim at the time of the attack was to destabilize the North Tower and send it crashing into the South Tower, toppling both skyscrapers.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Six people were killed and 1,042 others were injured in the attacks.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Following the bombing, floors that were blown out needed to be repaired to restore structural support.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] In February 2001, the Port Authority leased the entire World Trade Center complex to Vornado Realty Trust.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] However, Vornado insisted on last minute changes to the deal, and the next-highest bidder, Silverstein Properties, signed a lease for the complex on July 24, 2001.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] (EDT) on September 11, 2001, five hijackers affiliated with al-Qaeda crashed American Airlines Flight 11 into the northern facade of the North Tower between the 93rd and 99th floors.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] (EDT), a second group of five terrorists crashed the hijacked United Airlines Flight 175 into the southern facade of the South Tower, striking between the 77th and 85th floors.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] (EDT), the South Tower collapsed after burning for approximately 56 minutes.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] After burning for 102 minutes, the North Tower collapsed due to structural failure at 10:28 a.m.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] When the North Tower collapsed, debris fell on the nearby 7 World Trade Center, damaging it and starting fires.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The fires burned for hours, compromising the building's structural integrity.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Seven World Trade Center collapsed at 5:21 p.m.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] More than 90% of the workers and visitors who died in the towers had been at or above the points of impact.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] In the North Tower, 1,355 people at or above the point of impact were trapped, and died of smoke inhalation, fell, jumped from the tower to escape the smoke and flames, or were killed when the building eventually collapsed.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] One stairwell in the South Tower, Stairwell A, somehow avoided complete destruction, unlike the rest of the building.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] When Flight 11 hit, all three staircases in the North Tower's impact zone were destroyed, making it impossible for anyone above the 91st floor to escape.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] 107 people below the point of impact also died.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Minoru Yamasaki was the lead architect for the tower, and Emery Roth & Sons were the associate architects.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] During the World Trade Center's construction, the structural engineers ended up following draft versions of New York City's 1968 building codes, which incorporated "advanced techniques" in building design.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The Twin Towers used a tube-frame design, which required 40 percent less structural steel than conventional building designs.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The structures were inspired by the architectural ethic of Le Corbusier and was the seminal expression of Yamasaki's gothic modernist tendencies.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Yamasaki was also inspired by Islamic architecture, elements of which he incorporated in the buildings' design, having previously designed Saudi Arabia's Dhahran International Airport with the Saudi Binladin Group.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] When completed, the North Tower stood 1,368 feet (417.0 m) tall.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] It featured a 362-foot (110 m) telecommunications antenna or mast that was built on the roof in 1979 (upgraded in 1999 to accommodate DTV broadcasts).
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] With this addition, the highest point of the North Tower reached 1,730 feet (530 m).
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Each tower stood over 1,350 feet (410 m) high, and occupied about one acre (4,000 m2) of the total 16 acres (65,000 m2) of the site's land.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The Twin Towers' facades were made of high-strength, load-bearing perimeter steel columns which acted as Vierendeel trusses.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Although the columns themselves were lightweight, they were spaced closely together, forming a strong, rigid wall structure.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] There were 59 perimeter columns, narrowly spaced, on each side of the building.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] In all, the perimeter walls measured 207 feet (63 m) long on each side, and the corners were beveled.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The perimeter structure was constructed of prefabricated modular pieces connected by spandrel plates.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] From the 7th floor to the ground level, and down to the foundation, the columns were spaced 10 feet (3.0 m) apart to accommodate doorways.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] All columns were placed on bedrock 65–85 feet (20–26 m) below the surface.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The building's core housed the elevator and utility shafts, restrooms, three stairwells, and other support spaces.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The core of each tower was a rectangular area 87 by 135 feet (27 by 41 m), and contained 47 steel columns running from the bedrock to the top of the tower.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The North Tower's structural core was oriented with the long axis east to west.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The core columns supported about half the towers' weight.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Each building had three stairwells, also in the core, except on the mechanical floors.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The large, column-free space between the perimeter and core was bridged by prefabricated floor trusses, which connected to the perimeter columns.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Hat trusses (or "outrigger truss") located from the 107th floor to the top of the North and South towers were designed to support a tall communication antenna on top of each building.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Only the North Tower actually had an antenna fitted, which was added in 1978.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The framed-tube design using steel core and perimeter columns protected with sprayed-on fire resistant material created a relatively lightweight structure that would sway more in response to the wind.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] In designing the World Trade Center, Leslie Robertson considered the scenario of the impact of a jet airliner crashing into the building.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) found a three-page white paper that mentioned another aircraft impact analysis, involving impact of a jet at 600 mph (970 km/h), was indeed considered, but NIST could not locate the documentary evidence of the aircraft impact analysis.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Sprayed-fire resistant materials (SFRMs), gypsum wallboard, and vermiculite were used to provide fireproofing to the interiors.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] More fireproofing was added after a fire in February 1975, but after the 1993 bombing, inspections found fireproofing to be deficient.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The 1968 New York City building codes did not require sprinklers for high-rise buildings, except for underground spaces, but the entire complex was retrofitted by 2001.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The tenant list below was compiled from the original list provided by CoStar Group (a provider of electronic commercial real estate information), quoted by CNN, and was sourced from UnBlinking.com.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Cantor Fitzgerald's corporate headquarters were located in 1 World Trade Center.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The 92nd floor, though technically the first floor below Flight 11's impact zone, did not have any survivors.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Sixty-nine people reported to work that morning, including 67 employees of Carr Futures, a tenant on the 92nd floor.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The impact itself spared every single person on Floor 92 and did no damage to the floor directly.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] However, the force of the crash collapsed walls and inflicted nonstructural damage such as smashed windows, broken ceiling tiles and severed electrical wires, as well as causing knee-deep flooding throughout various rooms on the 92nd floor after the water pipes burst.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Multiple calls were recorded from people trapped on the floor, the workers reporting that although the stairs on the 92nd floor had not been destroyed, they were walled off by fallen debris from Flight 11's impact zone immediately above.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] In addition to the stairs being rendered impassable, the centralized impact into the North Tower's core also interrupted elevator service in the skyscraper from its 50th floor and higher, severing all escape routes for anyone above the 91st floor.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Initially, conditions on the 92nd floor were likely not dissimilar to what they were on the 91st, from which everyone survived and escaped.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Those who remained made their way to an unoccupied area on the west side of the floor that was initially free of smoke and fire.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] However, images show that the blaze on the tower's north face eventually spread westward to their safe haven in that section of the floor, making conditions there unsurvivable.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The last phone call from the North Tower came from Thomas McGinnis, a trader on the 92nd floor, when he got through to his wife Iliana at 10:18.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] McGinnis and a number of others had been confined to a conference room the entire time after the door jammed shut from the building buckling as the plane hit, separating them from everyone else on the floor.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Most of the floor was engulfed in flames by the time McGinnis called, with extremely limited space for the group to avoid being burned.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Despite his wife's attempts to reassure him, McGinnis did not believe they would survive.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The South Tower had already collapsed, and McGinnis revealed to her that he could see people jumping from the floors above.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] The line went dead at 10:26, two minutes before the tower collapsed.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Between 1978 and 1995, the Consulate of Paraguay was located in Suite 1609 of 1 World Trade Center.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Home Lines once occupied Suite 3969 from 1974 until 1988.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1-world-trade-center-1970-2001] Telerate Systems, Inc., which was subsumed by Dow Jones, occupied the 104th floor.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] An arson attack occurred at the One World Trade Center in Lower Manhattan, New York City, on February 12, 1975.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] The initial fire was started, and spread from the 11th floor to between the 9th and 14th floors, but was quickly extinguished by firefighters.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] The arsonist was later caught three months later on May 20 and was identified to be Oswald Adorno, a custodian working at the WTC, whose motive was because he was "disgruntled with his employer", said by Fire Commissioner Stephen J.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] There were no direct casualties and only minor injuries were sustained, with a few cases of smoke inhalation; costs in damages were estimated to be $1,000,000.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] In 1981, a $45 million sprinkler system was approved and began installation into the building as a result of the fire.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] A few city laws regarding fire safety were updated as well.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] On February 12, 1975, at approximately 11:45 p.m., a three alarm fire broke out upon the 11th floor in the offices of the B.F.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] Goodrich Company within the north tower of the World Trade Center.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] The fire later spread onto six other floors between the 9th and 14th floor through the tower's inner-service core via telephone cables in a cable shaft, though did not spread to other rooms or onto the hallways.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] Flames from the broken windows of the 11th floor could be seen; the broken windows may indicate that the fire had reached well over 700 °C.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] The fire was extinguished almost immediately and the original fire was extinguished within three hours.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] At the time of the event, no cause of the fire was known.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] Ralph Graniela and Thomas Flanagan, both fire marshals, worked undercover at the tower, posing as maintenance crew to try to find and catch the arsonist.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] On May 19, 1975, the undercover fire marshals began to suspect 19-year-old Oswald Adorno, a custodian working at the WTC, for starting the fire.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] On May 20, 1975, Adorno was taken by fire marshals to the First Police Precinct Station; he spontaneously admitted that he was the one responsible for the fire in February of the WTC.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] Murphy said Adorno told fire marshals his motive for starting the fire was because he was "disgruntled with his employer.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] He said he wasn't being given proper recognition." Deputy Chief Fire Marshal Michael O'Connor adds, "He said his boss made him work too hard, made him cover too many floors." Adorno was charged with seven charges of second-degree arson.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] Sixteen firemen were treated at the scene for smoke inhalation and minor injuries with twenty more firemen being treated after the fire as well as twenty firemen and eight WTC occupants treated for exposure to smoke and minor injuries.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] Albert Ullman, an export specialist with R.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] Saunders, Inc., reportedly had a heart attack while coming to work one morning to find his office space burnt.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] He was rushed to Beekman-Downtown Hospital where he was pronounced dead.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] Though spreading across about 65% of the 11th floor's office section, the fire caused no serious structural damage to the tower and no trusses were in need of replacing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] A spokesperson for the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey reported only the 11th floor was burned, the 10th and 9th floor suffered extensive water damage and smoke damage was extended to the 15th floor.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] Costs and damages were estimated to be $1,000,000 which urged the need of nine offices to be relocated within the WTC.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] On March 12, 1981, Port Authority began construction of a sprinkler system within the north tower of a cost of $45 million as a result of the major fire that happened six years prior.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] New York City laws were updated to require structures with floors to be divided into units of 7,500 square feet or less.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1975-world-trade-center-fire] Additionally, the law was updated to require smoke-detection systems that shut down the air-conditioning system in event of a fire to prevent spreading of the fire.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On October 23, 1983, two truck bombs were detonated at buildings in Beirut, Lebanon, housing American and French service members of the Multinational Force in Lebanon (MNF), a military peacekeeping operation during the Lebanese Civil War.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The attack killed 307 people: 241 U.S. and 58 French military personnel, six civilians and two of the attackers.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Another 128 Americans were wounded in the blast.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Thirteen later died of their injuries, and they are counted among the number who died.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] An elderly Lebanese man, a custodian/vendor who was known to work and sleep in his concession stand next to the building, was also killed in the first blast.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The explosives used were later estimated to be equivalent to as much as 12,000 pounds (5,400 kg) of TNT.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Minutes later, a second suicide bomber struck the nine-story *Drakkar* building, a few kilometers away, where the French contingent was stationed.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Fifty-five paratroopers from the 1st Parachute Chasseur Regiment and three paratroopers of the 9th Parachute Chasseur Regiment were killed and 15 injured.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] It was the single worst French military loss since the end of the Algerian War.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The wife and four children of a Lebanese janitor at the French building were also killed, and more than twenty other Lebanese civilians were injured.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] A group called Islamic Jihad claimed responsibility for the bombings and said that the aim was to force the MNF out of Lebanon.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] According to Caspar Weinberger, then United States Secretary of Defense, there is no knowledge of who did the bombing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Some analysis highlights the role of Hezbollah and Iran, calling it "an Iranian operation from top to bottom".
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] There is no consensus on whether Hezbollah existed at the time of bombing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The attacks eventually led to the withdrawal of the international peacekeeping force from Lebanon, where they had been stationed following the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) withdrawal in the aftermath of Israel's 1982 invasion of Lebanon.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] (MAU) are deployed in Beirut as part of a peacekeeping force to oversee the evacuation of Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) guerrillas.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] – The PLO retreats from Beirut under MNF protection.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Subsequently, the 32nd MAU is ordered out of Beirut by the President of the United States.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] – Lebanon's President, Bachir Gemayel, is assassinated.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] , in the hills overlooking Beirut, in support of the Lebanese Army, after it is nearly overrun by Syrian-backed Druze militiamen and Palestinian guerrillas.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Over 300 rounds of 5" shells are fired to suppress the attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] – The Beirut residence of the U.S. ambassador is shelled; for a second day U.S. naval ships again conduct counter fire operations.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] is redeployed to Beirut (primarily at the BIA) rejoining 2,200 French and Italian MNF troops already in place.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] – The 32nd MAU is relieved by the 24th MAU.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] – The 32nd MAU, redesignated as the 22nd MAU, returns to Lebanon to relieve the 24th MAU.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] in Beirut kills 63, of whom 17 are Americans.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On June 6, 1982, the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) initiated Operation "Peace for Galilee" and invaded Lebanon in order to create a 40 km buffer zone between the PLO and Syrian forces in Lebanon and Israel.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The Israeli invasion was tacitly approved by the U.S., and the U.S. provided overt military support to Israel in the form of arms and materiel.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The U.S.' support for Israel's invasion of Lebanon taken in conjunction with U.S. support for Lebanese President Bachir Gemayel and the Lebanese Armed Forces (LAF) alienated many.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Bachir Gemayel was the legally elected president, but he was a partisan Maronite Christian and covert associate of Israel.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] These factors served to disaffect the Lebanese Muslim and Druze communities.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] This animosity was made worse by the Phalangist, a right-wing, largely Maronite-Lebanese militia force closely associated with President Gemayel.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The Phalangist militia was responsible for multiple, bloody attacks against the Muslim and Druze communities in Lebanon and for the 1982 atrocities committed in the PLO refugee camps, Sabra and Shatila by Lebanese Forces (LF), while the IDF provided security and looked on.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The Phalangist militia's attacks on Sabra and Shatila were purportedly a response to the September 14, 1982, assassination of President-elect Bachir Gemayel.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Amine Gemayel, Bachir's brother, succeeded Bachir as the elected president of Lebanon, and Amine continued to represent and advance Maronite interests.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] All of this, according to British foreign correspondent Robert Fisk, served to generate ill will against the MNF among Lebanese Muslims and especially among the Shiites living in the slums of West Beirut.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Lebanese Muslims believed the MNF, and the Americans in particular, were unfairly siding with the Maronite Christians in their attempt to dominate Lebanon.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] As a result, this led to artillery, mortar, and small arms fire being directed at MNF peacekeepers by Muslim factions.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Operating under the peacetime rules of engagement, MNF peacekeepers – primarily U.S. and French forces – used minimum use of force as possible in order to avoid compromising their neutral status.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Do not chamber a round unless instructed to do so by a commissioned officer unless you must act in immediate self-defense where deadly force is authorized.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Keep ammo for crew-served weapons readily available but not loaded in the weapon.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Call local forces to assist in self-defense effort.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Use only minimum degree of force to accomplish any mission.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Stop the use of force when it is no longer needed to accomplish the mission.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] If you receive effective hostile fire, direct your fire at the source.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Respect civilian property; do not attack it unless absolutely necessary to protect friendly forces.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Respect and protect recognized medical agencies such as Red Cross, Red Crescent, etc.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Marine headquarters on the morning of October 23, 1983, were in full compliance with rules 1–3 and were unable to shoot fast enough to disable or stop the bomber (see Bombings: Sunday, October 23, 1983 below).
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] In 1982, the Islamic Republic of Iran established a base in the Syrian-controlled Beqaa Valley in Lebanon.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] From that base, Iran's Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) founded, financed, trained and equipped Hezbollah to operate as a proxy army for Iran.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] A few weeks before the bombing, Iran warned that providing armaments to Iran's enemies would provoke retaliatory punishment.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On September 26, 1983, "the National Security Agency (NSA) intercepted an Iranian diplomatic communications message from the Iranian intelligence agency, the Ministry of Information and Security (MOIS)," to its ambassador, Ali Akbar Mohtashemi, in Damascus.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The message directed the ambassador to "take spectacular action against the American Marines." The intercepted message, dated September 26, would not be passed to the Marines until October 26: three days after the bombing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Much of what is now public knowledge of Iranian involvement in the bombings, such as the purported supply of PETN by Iran and the suicide bomber's name and nationality, was not revealed to the public until the 2003 trial, *Peterson, et al v.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Testimony by Admiral James "Ace" Lyon's, U.S.N.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] (Ret), and FBI forensic explosive investigator Danny A.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Defenbaugh, plus a deposition by a Hezbollah operative named Mahmoud (a pseudonym) were particularly revealing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On July 14, 1983, a Lebanese Armed Forces patrol was ambushed by Lebanese Druze militia elements and from July 15–17, Lebanese troops engaged the Shia Amal militia in Beirut over a dispute involving the eviction of Shiite squatters from a schoolhouse.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] At the same time, fighting in the Shuf between the LAF and Druze militia escalated sharply.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On July 22, Beirut International Airport (BIA), the headquarters of the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] 24th Marine Amphibious Unit (24th MAU), was shelled with Druze mortar and artillery fire, wounding three U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Marines and causing the temporary closure of the airport.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On July 23, Walid Jumblatt, leader of the predominantly Druze Progressive Socialist Party (PSP), announced the formation of a Syrian-backed "National Salvation Front" opposed to the May 17 Agreement.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] In anticipation of an IDF withdrawal from the Alayh and Shuf districts, fighting between the Druze and LF and between the Druze and LAF, intensified during the month of August.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Druze artillery closed the BIA between 10 and 16 August, and the Druze made explicit their opposition to LAF deployment in the Shuf.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The LAF also clashed with the Amal militia in Beirut's western and southern suburbs.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] As the security situation deteriorated, US positions at BIA were subjected to increased fire.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On August 10 and 11, an estimated thirty-five rounds of mortar and rocket fire landed on US positions, wounding one marine.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On August 28, in response to constant mortar and rocket fire upon US positions, US peacekeepers returned fire for the first time.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On the following day, US artillery silenced a Druze battery after two marines were killed in a mortar attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On August 31, the LAF swept through the Shia neighborhood of West Beirut, establishing temporary control over the area.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On September 4, the IDF withdrew from the Alayh and Shuf Districts, falling back to the Awwali River.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The LAF was not prepared to fill the void, moving instead to occupy the key junction at Khaldah, south of BIA.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] That same day, BIA was again shelled, killing two Marines and wounding two others.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] No retaliation was given due to the ROE.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] As the LAF moved slowly eastward into the foothills of the Shuf, accounts of massacres, conducted by Christians and Druze alike, began to be reported.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On September 5, a Druze force, reportedly reinforced by PLO elements, routed the Christian LF militia at Bhamdun and all but eliminated the LF as a military factor in the Alayh District.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] This defeat obliged the LAF to occupy Souk El Gharb to avoid conceding all of the high ground overlooking BIA to the Druze.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] U.S. positions were again subjected to constant indirect fire attacks; consequently, counterbattery fire based on target acquisition radar data was employed.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] F-14 tactical airborne reconnaissance (TARPS) missions were conducted for the first time on September 7.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On September 8, naval gunfire from offshore destroyers was employed for the first time in defense of the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On September 25, a ceasefire was instituted that same day and Beirut International Airport reopened five days later.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On October 1, Walid Jumblatt announced a separate governmental administration for the Shuf and called for the mass defection of all Druze elements from the LAF.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Nevertheless, on 14 October the leaders of Lebanon's key factions agreed to conduct reconciliation talks in Geneva, Switzerland.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Although the ceasefire officially held into mid-October, factional clashes intensified and sniper attacks on MNF contingents became commonplace.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On October 19, four Marines were wounded when a US convoy was attacked by a remotely detonated car bomb parked along the convoy route.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On October 16, thousands of Shia pilgrims were holding a procession celebrating Ashura in Nabatieh when an Israeli military convoy attempted to pass along the same road as the pilgrims.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The Israelis, apparently unaware of the holiday or its significance, attempted to clear the road resulting in a confrontation which ended in an overturned jeep set alight, along with two transport trucks, and stone pelting.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The Israelis opened fire and tossed grenades resulting in at least two dead and fifteen wounded.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] This incident significantly increased tensions between the Shia community in Lebanon and Israel.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] This by extension, worsened increased tensions with the US.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] At around 06:22, a 19-ton yellow Mercedes-Benz stake-bed truck drove to the Beirut International Airport.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The 1st Battalion 8th Marines (BLT), commanded by Lieutenant Colonel Larry Gerlach, was a subordinate element of the 24th MAU.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The truck was not the water truck they had been expecting.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Instead, it was a hijacked truck carrying explosives.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The driver turned his truck onto an access road leading to the compound.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] He drove into and circled the parking lot, and then he accelerated to crash through a 5 feet (1.5 m)-high barrier of concertina wire separating the parking lot from the building.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The truck then passed between two sentry posts and through an open vehicle gate in the perimeter chain-link fence, crashed through a guard shack in front of the building and smashed into the lobby of the building serving as the barracks for the 1st Battalion 8th Marines (BLT).
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The sentries at the gate were operating under rules of engagement which made it very difficult to respond quickly to the truck.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On the day of the bombing, the sentries were ordered to keep a loaded magazine inserted in their weapon, bolt closed, weapon on safe and no round in the chamber.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Only one sentry, LCpl Eddie DiFranco, was able to chamber a round.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] However, by that time the truck was already crashing into the building's entryway.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The suicide bomber, an Iranian national named Ismail Ascari, detonated his explosives, which were later estimated to be equivalent to approximately 12,000 pounds of TNT.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The force of the explosion collapsed the four-story building into rubble, crushing to death 241 American servicemen.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] According to Eric Hammel in his history of the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The explosive mechanism was a gas-enhanced device consisting of compressed butane in canisters employed with pentaerythritol tetranitrate (PETN) to create a fuel-air explosive.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The bomb was carried on a layer of concrete covered with a slab of marble to direct the blast upward.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Despite the lack of sophistication and wide availability of its component parts, a gas-enhanced device can be a lethal weapon.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] These devices were similar to fuel-air or thermobaric weapons, explaining the large blast and damage.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] An after-action forensic investigation by the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) determined that the bomb was so powerful that it probably would have brought down the building even if the sentries had managed to stop the truck between the gate and the building.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Less than ten minutes later, a similar attack occurred against the barracks of the French 3rd Company of the 1st Parachute Chasseur Regiment, 6 kilometres (3.7 mi) away in the Ramlet al Baida area of West Beirut.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] As the suicide bomber drove his pickup truck toward the "Drakkar" building, French paratroopers began shooting at the truck and its driver.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] It is believed that the driver was killed and the truck was immobilized and rolled to stop about 15 yards (14 m) from the building.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] A few moments passed before the truck exploded, bringing down the nine-story building and killing 58 French paratroopers.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] It is believed that this bomb was detonated by remote control and that, though similarly constructed, it was smaller than and slightly less than half as powerful as the one used against the Marines.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Many of the paratroopers had gathered on their balconies moments earlier to see what was happening at the airport.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] It was France's worst military loss since the end of the Algerian War in 1962.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Agence France-Presse reported two days later that an unidentified individual allegedly belonging to the previously unheard of Free Islamic Revolution Movement called in and claimed responsibility for the attacks, naming the suicide bombers as 26-year-old Abu Mazen and 24-year-old Abu Sijaan.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Organized rescue efforts began immediately – within three minutes of the bombing – and continued for days.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Unit maintenance personnel were not billeted in the BLT building, and they rounded up pry bars, torches, jacks and other equipment from unit vehicles and maintenance shops and began rescue operations.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Meanwhile, combat engineers and truck drivers began using their organic assets, i.e., trucks and engineering equipment, to help with the rescue operations.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] 24th MAU medical personnel, Navy dentists LT Gil Bigelow and LT Jim Ware, established two aid stations to triage and treat casualties.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Medevac helicopters, CH-46s from Marine Medium Helicopter Squadron (HMM-162), were airborne by 6:45 AM.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Navy medical personnel from nearby vessels of the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Sixth Fleet went ashore to assist with treatment and medical evacuation of the injured, as did sailors and shipboard Marines who volunteered to assist with the rescue effort.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Lebanese, Italian, British, and even French troops, who had suffered their own loss, provided assistance.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Many Lebanese civilians voluntarily joined the rescue effort.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Especially important was a Lebanese construction contractor, Rafiq Hariri of the firm Oger-Liban, who provided heavy construction equipment, e.g., a 40-ton P & H crane, etc., from nearby BIA worksites.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Hariri's construction equipment proved vitally necessary in lifting and removing heavy slabs of concrete debris at the barracks site just as it had been necessary in assisting with clearing debris after the April U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] While the rescuers were at times hindered by hostile sniper and artillery fire, several Marine survivors were pulled from the rubble at the BLT 1/8 bomb site and airlifted by helicopter to the USS *Iwo Jima*, located offshore.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Air Force and Royal Air Force medevac planes transported the seriously wounded to the hospital at RAF Akrotiri in Cyprus and to U.S. and German hospitals in West Germany.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Gerlach, were sent to the Italian MNF dispensary and to Lebanese hospitals in Beirut.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Israel's offers to medevac the wounded to hospitals in Israel were rejected as politically unacceptable even though Israeli hospitals were known to provide excellent care and were considerably closer than hospitals in Germany.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] At about noon Sunday, October 23, the last survivor was pulled from the rubble; he was LTJG Danny G.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Other men survived beyond Sunday, but they succumbed to their injuries before they could be extracted from the rubble.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] By Wednesday, the majority of the bodies and body parts had been recovered from the stricken barracks, and the recovery effort ended on Friday.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] After five days, the FBI came in to investigate, and the Marines returned to normal duties.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] "The explosion at the French barracks blew the whole building off its foundations and threw it about 6 meters (20 feet) westward, while breaking the windows of almost every apartment house in the neighborhood ....
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The explosions resulted in 346 casualties, of which 234 (68%) were killed immediately, with head injuries, thoracic injuries and burns accounting for a large number of deaths.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The New York Times printed a list of the identified casualties on October 26, 1983.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Another list of those who survived the incident was published by the Department of Defense.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The information had to be re-printed, as individuals were misidentified, and family members were told incorrect statuses of their loved ones.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Twenty-one U.S. peacekeepers who lost their lives in the bombing were buried in Section 59 at Arlington National Cemetery, near one of the memorials to all the victims.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] President Ronald Reagan called the attack a "despicable act" and pledged to keep a military force in Lebanon.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger, who had privately advised the administration against stationing U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Marines in Lebanon, said there would be no change in the U.S.'s Lebanon policy.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] French President François Mitterrand and other French dignitaries visited both the French and American bomb sites to offer their personal condolences on Monday, October 24, 1983.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] During his visit, President Mitterrand visited each of the scores of American caskets and made the sign of the cross as his mark of respectful observance for each of the fallen peacekeepers.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Bush arrived and made a tour of the destroyed BLT barracks on Wednesday, October 26, 1983.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Vice President Bush toured the site and said the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] "would not be cowed by terrorists." Vice President Bush visited with wounded U.S. personnel aboard the U.S.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] *Iwo Jima* (LPH-2), and he took time to meet with the commanders of the other MNF units, French, Italian and British, deployed in Beirut.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] In retaliation for the attacks, France launched an airstrike in the Beqaa Valley against alleged Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) positions.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] President Reagan assembled his national security team and planned to target the Sheik Abdullah barracks in Baalbek, Lebanon, which housed Iran's Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) believed to be training Hezbollah militants.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] A joint American–French air assault on the camp where the bombing was planned was also approved by Reagan and Mitterrand.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Defense Secretary Weinberger lobbied successfully against the mission, because at the time it was not certain that Iran was behind the attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Marines in Beirut were moved to transport vessels offshore where they could not be targeted; yet, they would be ready and available to serve as a ready reaction force in Beirut if needed.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] For protection against snipers and artillery attacks, the Marines remaining at the airport built, and moved into, bunkers in the ground employing 'appropriated' Soviet-bloc CONEXes.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Geraghty requested and received reinforcements to replace his unit losses.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] BLT 2/6, the Second Marine Division Air Alert Battalion stationed at Camp Lejeune, North Carolina, and commanded by Col.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Kelley, Jr., was dispatched and flown into Beirut by four C-141s in less than 36 hours after the bombing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Kelley officially replaced the seriously injured BLT 1/8 commander, Lt.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The entire Headquarters and Service Company and Weapons Company of BLT 2/6 was airlifted into Beirut, along with Company E (Reinforced).
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Kelley quietly redesignated his unit, BLT 2/6, as BLT 1/8 to help bolster the morale of the BLT 1/8 survivors.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The BLT headquarters was relocated to a landfill area west of the airfield, and Company A (Reinforced) was repositioned from the university library position to serve as landing force reserve afloat, aboard Amphibious Ready Group shipping.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On November 18, 1983, the 22d MAU rotated into Beirut and relieved in place the 24th MAU.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Kelley commanding BLT 1/8 returned to Camp Lejeune, NC, by sea for training and refitting.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Eventually, it became evident that the U.S. would launch no serious and immediate retaliatory attack for the Beirut Marine barracks bombing beyond naval barrages and air strikes used to interdict continuous harassing fire from Druze and Syrian missile and artillery sites.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] A true retaliatory strike failed to materialize because there was a rift in White House counsel, largely between George P.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Shultz of the Department of State and Weinberger of the Department of Defense.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Secretary of State Shultz was an advocate for retaliation, but Secretary of Defense Caspar Weinberger was against it.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Geraghty would be blamed for security lapses prior to the barracks bombings.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] In the following months the U.S. force at the Beirut airport endured frequent shelling.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Weinberger urged withdrawal of the MNF, but Reagan, with the support of the State Department and the NSC staff, left it in place.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The USS *New Jersey* had arrived and taken up station off Beirut on September 25, 1983.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Special Representative in the Middle East Robert McFarlane's team had requested *New Jersey* after the August 29th Druze mortar attack that killed two marines.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] After the October 23rd bombing, on November 28, the U.S. government announced that the *New Jersey* would remain stationed off Beirut although her crew would be rotated.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On December 14, *New Jersey* fired 11 projectiles from her 16-inch guns at hostile targets near Beirut.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Also in December 1983, U.S. aircraft from the USS *John F.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Kennedy* and USS *Independence* battle groups attacked Syrian targets in Lebanon, but this was ostensibly in response to Syrian missile attacks on American warplanes.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] In the meantime, the attack boosted the prestige and growth of the Shi'ite organization Hezbollah.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Hezbollah officially denied any involvement in the attacks, but was seen by many Lebanese as involved nonetheless as it praised the "two martyr mujahideen" who "set out to inflict upon the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Administration an utter defeat, not experienced since Vietnam." Hezbollah was now seen by many as "the spearhead of the sacred Muslim struggle against foreign occupation".
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Amal Movement leader Nabih Berri, who had previously supported U.S. mediation efforts, asked the U.S. and France to leave Lebanon and accused the two countries of seeking to commit 'massacres' against the Lebanese and of creating a "climate of racism" against Shias.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Islamic Jihad phoned in new threats against the MNF pledging that "the earth would tremble" unless the MNF withdrew by New Year's Day 1984.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On February 7, 1984, President Reagan ordered the Marines to begin withdrawing from Lebanon largely because of waning congressional support for the mission after the attacks on the barracks.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The withdrawal of the 22d MAU from the BIA was completed 12:37 PM on February 26, 1984.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] "Fighting between the Lebanese Army and Druze militia in the nearby Shouf mountains provided a noisy backdrop to the Marine evacuation.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On February 8, 1984, the USS *New Jersey* fired almost 300 shells at Druze and Syrian positions in the Beqaa Valley east of Beirut.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] This was the heaviest shore bombardment since the Korean War.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Firing without air spotting, the battleship had to rely on Israeli target intelligence.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] "In a nine-hour period, the USS *New Jersey* fired 288 16-inch rounds, each one weighing as much as a Volkswagen Beetle.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] In those nine-hours, the ship consumed 40 percent of the 16-inch ammunition available in the entire European theater ... [and] in one burst of wretched excess," *New Jersey* seemed to be unleashing eighteen months of repressed fury.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Following the lead of the U.S., the rest of the multinational force, the British, French and Italians, was withdrawn by the end of February 1984.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The ship-borne 22d MAU contingent remained stationed offshore near Beirut while a detached 100-man ready reaction force remained stationed ashore near the U.S./U.K.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The 22d MAU was relieved in place by the 24th MAU on April 10, 1984.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On April 21, the ready reaction force in Beirut was deactivated and its men were reassigned to their respective ships.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] In late July 1984, the last Marines from the 24th MAU, the U.S./U.K.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Embassy guard detail, was withdrawn from Beirut.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] A 2019 study disputes that the bombings motivated the withdrawal of U.S. forces, arguing instead that the collapse of the Lebanese national army in February 1984 was the primary motivating factor behind the withdrawal.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] At the time of the bombing, an obscure group called the "Islamic Jihad" claimed responsibility for the attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] There were many in the U.S. government, such as Vice President Bush, Secretary of State George Shultz, and National Security Adviser Robert McFarlane, who was formerly Reagan's Mideast envoy, who believed Iran and/or Syria were/was responsible for the bombings.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] After some years of investigation, the U.S. government now believes that elements of what would eventually become Hezbollah, backed by Iran and Syria, were responsible for these bombings as well as the bombing of the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] It is believed that Hezbollah used the name "Islamic Jihad" to remain anonymous.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Hezbollah eventually announced its existence in 1985.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Hezbollah, Iran and Syria have continued to deny any involvement in any of the bombings.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] An Iranian group erected a monument in a cemetery in Tehran to commemorate the 1983 bombings and its "martyrs" in 2004.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Two years after the bombing, a U.S. grand jury secretly indicted Imad Mughniyah for terrorist activities.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Mughniyah was never captured, but he was killed by a car bomb in Syria on February 12, 2008.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Commentators argue that the lack of a response by the Americans emboldened terrorist organizations to conduct further attacks against U.S. targets.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Along with the U.S. embassy bombing, the barracks bombing prompted the Inman Report, a review of the security of U.S. facilities overseas for the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] State Department added Fuad Shukr to its Rewards for Justice Program, stating that he played a central role in the bombings.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Shukr was killed in an Israeli airstrike in Beirut on July 30, 2024.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Ibrahim Aqil, who also had a bounty for the same reason, was killed in a separate Israeli airstrike on September 20, 2024.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Both assassinations took place amid the Israel–Hezbollah conflict of 2023-2024.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On March 8, 1985, a truck bomb blew up in Beirut, killing more than 80 people and injuring more than 200.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The bomb detonated near the apartment block of Sheikh Mohammad Hussein Fadlallah, a Shia cleric thought by many to be the spiritual leader of Hezbollah.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Shortly after the barracks bombing, President Ronald Reagan appointed a military fact-finding committee headed by retired Admiral Robert L.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The commission's report found senior military officials responsible for security lapses and blamed the military chain of command for the disaster.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] It suggested that there might have been many fewer deaths if the barracks guards had carried loaded weapons and a barrier more substantial than the barbed wire the bomber drove over easily.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The commission also noted that the "prevalent view" among U.S. commanders was that there was a direct link between the navy shelling of the Muslims at Suq-al-Garb and the truck bomb attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On October 3 and December 28, 2001, the families of the 241 U.S. peacekeepers who were killed as well as several injured survivors filed civil suits against the Islamic Republic of Iran and the Ministry of Information and Security (MOIS) in the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] District Court for the District of Columbia.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Iran, the defendant, was served with the two complaints, one from Deborah D.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Peterson, Personal Representative of the Estate of James C.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Knipple, et al., the other from Joseph and Marie Boulos, Personal Representatives of the Estate of Jeffrey Joseph Boulos, on May 6 and July 17, 2002.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Iran denied responsibility for the attack but did not file any response to the claims of the families.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Lamberth entered defaults against defendants in both cases.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] On May 30, 2003, Lamberth found Iran legally responsible for providing Hezbollah with financial and logistical support that helped them carry out the attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The judgment was divided up among the victims; the largest award was $12 million to Larry Gerlach, who became a paraplegic as a result of a broken neck he suffered in the attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The attorney for the families of the victims uncovered some new information, including a U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] National Security Agency intercept of a message sent from Iranian intelligence headquarters in Tehran to Hojjat ol-eslam Ali-Akbar Mohtashemi, the Iranian ambassador in Damascus.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Lamberth, "The message directed the Iranian ambassador to contact Hussein Musawi, the leader of the terrorist group Islamic Amal, and to instruct him ...
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Musawi's Islamic Amal was a breakaway faction of the Amal Movement and an autonomous part of embryonic Hezbollah.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] According to Muhammad Sahimi, high-ranking US officials had a different interpretation from that intercept, which stopped them from ordering a revengeful attack against Iran.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] In July 2012, federal Judge Royce Lamberth ordered Iran to pay more than $813m in damages and interest to the families of the 241 U.S. peacekeepers that were killed, writing in a ruling that Tehran had to be "punished to the fullest extent legally possible...
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Iran is racking up quite a bill from its sponsorship of terrorism." In April 2016, the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Supreme Court ruled that frozen assets of Iran's Central Bank held in the U.S. could be used to pay the compensation to families of the victims.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Former Mossad agent Victor Ostrovsky, in his 1990 book *By Way of Deception*, has accused the Mossad of knowing the specific time and location of the bombing, but only gave general information to the Americans of the attack, information which was worthless.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] According to Ostrovsky, then Mossad head Nahum Admoni decided against giving the specific details to the Americans on the grounds that the Mossad's responsibility was to protect Israel's interests, not Americans.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Admoni denied having any prior knowledge of the attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The Ayatollah backed group called Iran Suicide Brigades which encouraged new 'suicide units' to be formed by willing volunteers were behind the monument.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] A Beirut Memorial has been established at Marine Corps Base Camp Lejeune, and has been used as the site of annual memorial services for the victims of the attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] A Beirut Memorial Room at the USO in Jacksonville, North Carolina has also been created.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The Armed Forces Chaplaincy Center, the site of Chaplain Corps training for the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Army, Navy, and Air Force at Fort Jackson, Columbia, South Carolina, includes the partially destroyed sign from the Beirut barracks chapel as a memorial to those who died in the attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] According to Rabbi Arnold Resnicoff, one of the navy chaplains present during the attack, "Amidst the rubble, we found the plywood board which we had made for our "Peace-keeping Chapel." The Chaplain Corps Seal had been hand-painted, with the words "Peace-keeping" above it, and "Chapel" beneath.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Now "Peace-keeping" was legible, but the bottom of the plaque was destroyed, with only a few burned and splintered pieces of wood remaining.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Other memorials to the victims of the Beirut barracks bombing have been erected in various locations within the U.S., including one at Penn's Landing in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, Boston, Massachusetts, and one in Florida.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] A Lebanese cedar has been planted in Arlington National Cemetery near the graves of some of the victims of the attack, in their memory.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] One memorial to the attack is located outside the U.S., where Gilla Gerzon, the director of the Haifa, Israel USO during the time of the attack coordinated the creation of a memorial park that included 241 olive trees, one for each of the U.S. military personnel who died in the attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] The trees lead to an overpass on Mount Carmel looking toward Beirut.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] There is also an ongoing effort on the part of Beirut veterans and family members to convince the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Postal Service and Citizens' Stamp Advisory Committee to create a stamp in memory of the victims of the attack, but the recommendation has not yet been approved.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] In the meantime, Beirut veterans have created a "PC Postage" commercially produced Beirut Memorial statue private vendor stamp (with or without the words "They Came in Peace") that is approved for use as postage by the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1983-beirut-barracks-bombing] Author and former Navy SEAL Jack Carr published a book about the 1983 bombings, entitled *Targeted* in late 2024.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] On 29 December 1992, a series of bombings targeted two hotels which housed United States Marines en route to deploy in Somalia as part of Operation Restore Hope in Aden, Yemen.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Orchestrated by Islamic Jihad in Yemen senior leader Jamal al-Nahdi, the bombs were planted at a restaurant in the Gold Mohur Hotel and the parking lot of the Aden Mövenpick Hotel, though the bomb at the latter hotel exploded prematurely.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Marines were harmed in the attacks, which instead killed an Austrian tourist and a hotel employee at the Gold Mohur, and injured seven others altogether.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The next day, the U.S. government announced the evacuation of all U.S. forces still stationed in Yemen for the Operation in Somalia.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The bombings are sometimes considered to be al-Qaeda's first attacks against the U.S. due to the connections that Islamic Jihad in Yemen, including its leader Tariq al-Fadhli, had to Osama bin Laden financially.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Bin Laden would later take credit for the attacks in 1998.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] In the months after the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan in February 1989, Osama bin Laden decided upon the socialists of South Yemen being the next target of his *mujahideen* allies as well as those directly part of his newly-formed militant group, al-Qaeda.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] While residing in Saudi Arabia, he devised a plan to start an Islamist guerrilla war with the assistance of Tariq al-Fadhli, a fellow Afghan Arab who showed a similar disdain for the socialists, who had removed his family from power as leaders of the Fadhli Sultanate and forced them into exile.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] With funding from Bin Laden, Fadhli set out to the mountains of his native Abyan Governorate, where he set up a training camp alongside other former fighters from Afghanistan in mid-1990.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Many other Afghan Arabs had set up training camps funded by Bin Laden across Yemen in the months after its unification in May 1990.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] President Ali Abdullah Saleh, previously the leader of North Yemen before unification, condoned their arrival and sought to use them to undermine the stability of the south in order to solidify his grip on power.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Bush announced Operation Restore Hope, a United States-led military peacekeeping effort meant to provide stability and humanitarian aid to Somalia amid the civil war.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Saleh agreed to have American military units utilize Aden and its port as a connecting point to reach Somalia.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Bin Laden feared that this agreement would act as an effort by the US to further expand its presence in the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] He had grown furious after the Saudi government agreed to indefinitely host US military bases in their country in the aftermath of the Gulf War.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] From his new base of operations in Sudan, Bin Laden decided that he would have to act in order to prevent the US from establishing a permanent occupation in the region.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] According to Simon Reeve in *The New Jackals*, al-Qaeda commander Muhammad Atef travelled to Somalia in order to investigate and determine any methods by which the group could attack US and UN forces involved in the operation.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Consulting Bin Laden and the groups shura council, they decided upon forces stationed in Yemen being their target.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] In late December 1992, as Fadhli and his men were in the midst of waging their insurgency, Bin Laden contacted another local jihadist ally, Jamal al-Nahdi, to carry out an attack based on reports he received from al-Qaeda operatives detailing the US military presence in Aden.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Nahdi, who also fought in Afghanistan, was one of the first people to pledge allegiance to al-Qaeda upon its formation.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Bin Laden subscribed to the policy of "centralization of decision and decentralization of execution", allowing Nahdi to plan out the specifics of the attacks.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Numerous sources, including the Federal Bureau of Investigation, state that Fadhli was also involved in the attacks to some extent, ranging from him being the mastermind to simply a co-conspirator with Nahdi.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] On 23 December 1992, during a meeting at his apartment in Aden, Nahdi laid out his plan to a handful of militants, many of whom attended a training camp in northern Yemen funded by Bin Laden.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The plan had begun to go awry by 28 December, the day before it was set to take place.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Local socialist authorities had arrested the two militants who were set to handle the explosives at the airport.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Nahdi managed to convince his cell to still go through with the attacks, and tasked another man, Salih al-Khanabashi, with detonating the explosives at the airport, which had already been buried near the site.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] On 29 December 1992, Nahdi along with an assistant planted a bomb in an upper floor of the Gold Mohur Hotel, a luxury hotel by the beachfront of Aden.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The two then drove to the Aden Mövenpick Hotel, where they attempted to plant a bomb in the parking lot.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] As Nahdi was handling the explosives, the detonator was accidentally triggered, producing a blast which nearly severed his hand.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] As his assistant attempted to stop the bleeding, the bomb at the Gold Mohur had detonated.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The blast took place by a packed restaurant inside the hotel, shattering windows and heavily damaging support beams and a hallway.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] No Marines were present at the Gold Mohur but were at the Mövenpick, Immediately following the blast that evening, the Marines left for the airfield.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Initially a three-plane detachment only two were on the tarmac at Aden Intl Airport.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] One plane was on a mission when the blast hit and was contacted enroute to turn back and land in Mombasa Kenya.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Through the night the Marines of VMGR 352 loaded three planes of equipment on to two KC-130s.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] At sunrise they had finished as three C5 Galaxies taxied in and parked with doors closed and engines idling.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The three camo green leviathans watched and waited for the Marines to leave for Mombasa Kenya.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Additionally, upon their arrival at the airport, Khanabashi and his partner found that the buried explosives had already been found and excavated, forcing them to abort the plan.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Thus, no US forces were harmed by the bombings, rendering it a failure.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] At the Gold Mohur, an Austrian tourist and Yemeni janitor were killed, along with four other Austrians being injured, two seriously.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The Mövenpick parking lot blast wounded Nahdi, his assistant, and a security officer who was approaching them as they were rigging the explosives.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Additional authorities soon arrived at the parking lot within minutes of the blast to apprehend the militants and neutralize the remaining explosives.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Authorities searching the car of the two perpetrators found 23 bombs, two anti-tank mines, two sticks of dynamite, two machine guns and a pistol.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The bombing did not attract much local or international media attention at the time.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Writing for *The Guardian*, journalist Kevin Rushby recalled that the Mövenpick had still been operating regularly just weeks after the attack, with patrons paying it no mind.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] There were no major reactions in the US either, as no American soldiers were among the casualties.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] However, the bombings led to anxiety among Yemenis who had previously condoned and endorsed the arrival of the Afghan Arabs, with "worried fathers and irate tribal shaykhs" soon coming to retrieve their sons from the militant camps until they had become nearly deserted.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Utilizing an opportunity to end the violence against the socialists, then-vice president and former South Yemen leader Ali Salem al-Beidh ordered a military crackdown on the jihadists.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The socialist-affiliated 3rd Armoured Division besieged Fadhli's camp in Abyan, but he managed to evade them after agreeing to travel to and surrender in Sanaa as part of a deal brokered by mediators sent by Saleh, who was thus able to retain an asset to use against the South.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The bailout infuriated Beidh, although Saleh assured to him and the international community that an investigation into the bombing would be conducted.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Nonetheless, Fadhli's arrest was the only disciplinary action conducted by the Saleh government relating to the bombing, and he was released months later to continue his attacks on the socialists, eventually siding with Saleh in the civil war of 1994.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Facing a siege, Khanabashi took refuge at and defended a camp in the mountains of southern Shabwah Governorate until he and his fellow jihadists managed to flee to the northern camp in Saada Governorate.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Facing depleting numbers and morale, they were eventually taken under the control of Abu Ali al-Harithi, an al-Qaeda commander who took part in the establishment of training camps across Yemen.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Nahdi along with other militants connected to the bombing were incarcerated at the al-Mansoura prison until he and five others escaped on 17 July 1993 with internal assistance.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Harithi then transported them as well as Khanabashi to Bin Laden's base-of-operations in Khartoum.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The U.S. government announced the withdrawal of their remaining troops stationed in Yemen for Operation Restore Hope on 30 December, in part due to the bombings.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] A spokesperson for the Pentagon downplayed the role that the bombings took in the decision to withdraw from Yemen, stating that by the time of the withdrawal Yemen was only transporting a single aircraft of soldiers per day.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] He said that "there was no longer a compelling need to use facilities there" and that "the primary reason was that the need for facilities had declined from the beginning of the operation".
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The withdrawal of US troops from Yemen shortly after the bombings were perceived by Bin Laden and al-Qaeda as a major victory.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The killing of non-Americans in the attacks provoked moral and theological uncertainty among some members of al-Qaeda.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] This eventually led to Mamdouh Mahmud Salim (Abu Hajer) providing a religious justification to the group regarding the killing of innocents.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] He referred to Ibn Taymiyya's endorsement of killing Mongols and anyone associating with them or simply in their vicinity, even Muslims, to affirm that the same concept could be applied to those caught in the crossfire of al-Qaeda's attacks.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] Gohel claims that the bombings were the first coordinated effort between Bin Laden and Ayman al-Zawahiri, alleging that Egyptian Islamic Jihad member Ahmad Mabruk had aided the perpetrators.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] In 1998, Bin Laden would take credit for the bombings, claiming, "The United States wanted to set up a military base for US soldiers in Yemen, so that it could send fresh troops to Somalia...
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The Arab mujaheddin related to the Afghan jihad carried out two bomb explosions in Yemen to warn the United States, causing damage to some Americans staying in those hotels.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] The United States received our warning and gave up the idea of setting up its military bases in Yemen.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1992-aden-hotel-bombings] This was the first al-Qaeda victory scored against the Crusaders." This was not entirely true, since no Americans were injured or killed, nor did the United States recognize this action as a warning.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] The ***1993 World Trade Center Bombing Memorial*** was created to commemorate the six lives lost during the February 26, 1993, bombing of the World Trade Center in New York City.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] The memorial was commissioned by the Port Authority of New York & New Jersey Art Commission after the events of the bombing, and completed in 1995.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] It was placed directly above the bomb's blast site —the public parking garage beneath the World Trade Center— and situated squarely between the Twin Towers in what was the Austin J.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] Tobin Plaza on the grounds of the World Trade Center complex.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] The Memorial, along with other valuable sculptures and pieces of artwork, was destroyed during the September 11 attacks in 2001.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] Designed by Elyn Zimmerman, the memorial and its surroundings were intentionally made to resemble a bullseye when observed from a bird's-eye view, as it was situated directly above the ground zero site of the bombing, between One World Trade Center and the Marriott World Trade Center Hotel.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] The interior of the fountain had purposely cracked, white granite walls that evoked the appearance of ancient tumulus markers—mounds of earth raised over graves.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] The walls enclosed a shallow pool that collected water flowing from a hole in the fountain's central red granite drum.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] All of the Memorial's inscriptions were arranged circumferentially.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] Out of respect for the families of victims Wilfredo Mercado and Monica Rodriguez Smith, Zimmerman included a Spanish translation of the corresponding inscription, found directly below its English counterpart.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] The names of each of the six victims, all World Trade Center employees, were also etched into the fountain.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] The fountain was destroyed with the rest of the World Trade Center during the September 11 attacks.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] After assessing the destruction of the memorial, along with the rest of the World Trade Center complex, only a single fragment of the inscribed granite marked "John D", from the name of John DiGiovanni, was found intact at Ground Zero.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] The fragment was later incorporated into a temporary memorial designed by Port Authority architect Jacqueline Hanley, and erected on the Liberty Street side of the site following the September 11 attacks.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] The memorial was visible across a fence barrier but was not open to the public.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] After the completion of the permanent memorial, the temporary memorial was dismantled.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] The fountain fragment is currently located at the National September 11 Memorial & Museum.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] The remainder of the fountain was never recovered, and any of its remains were removed from Ground Zero along with the rest of the rubble.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing-memorial] The names of the victims are now displayed on Panel N-73 at the North Pool's National September 11 Memorial & Museum.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] On February 26, 1993, Ramzi Yousef and associates carried out a van bomb terrorist attack below the North Tower of the World Trade Center in New York City.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The 1,336-pound (606 kg) urea nitrate–hydrogen gas enhanced device was intended to make the North Tower collapse onto the South Tower, taking down both skyscrapers and killing tens of thousands of people.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] While it failed to do so, it was successful in killing six people, and caused over a thousand injuries.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] About 50,000 people were evacuated from the buildings that day.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The attack was planned by a group of terrorists including Yousef, Ahmed Ajaj, Mahmud Abouhalima, Mohammed A.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Salameh, Eyad Ismoil, Nidal Ayyad, and Abdul Rahman Yasin.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In March 1994, four men were convicted of carrying out the bombing: Ajaj, Abouhalima, Ayyad, and Salameh.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The charges included conspiracy, explosive destruction of property, and interstate transportation of explosives.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In November 1997, two more were convicted: Ramzi Yousef, the organizer behind the bombings, and Eyad Ismoil, who drove the van carrying the bomb.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Emad Salem, an FBI informant and a key witness in the trial of Yousef, Abdul Hakim Murad, and Wali Khan Amin Shah, stated that the bomb itself was built under supervision from the FBI.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] During his time as an FBI informant, Salem recorded hours of telephone conversations with his FBI handlers.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In tapes made after the bombing, Salem alleged that an unnamed FBI supervisor declined to move forward on a plan that would have used a "phony powder" to fool the conspirators into believing that they were working with genuine explosives.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Yousef arrived illegally in the United States on September 1, 1992, traveling with Ahmed Ajaj from Pakistan, though both sat apart on the flight and acted as though they were traveling separately.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Ajaj tried to enter using a forged Swedish passport, though it had been altered and thus raised suspicions among Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS) officials at John F.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] When officials put Ajaj through secondary inspection, they discovered bomb-making instructions and other materials in his luggage, and arrested him.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The name Abu Barra, an alias of Mohammed Jamal Khalifa, appeared in the manuals.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Yousef entered on a false Iraqi passport claiming political asylum, and was given a hearing date.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Yousef set up residence in Jersey City, New Jersey, traveled around New York and New Jersey and called Sheikh Omar Abdel-Rahman, a controversial blind Muslim cleric, via cell phone.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] After being introduced to his co-conspirators by Abdel Rahman at the latter's Al-Farooq Mosque in Brooklyn, Yousef began assembling the 1,500-pound (680 kg) urea nitrate–hydrogen gas enhanced device for delivery to the WTC.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] He ordered chemicals from his hospital room when he had been injured in a car crash – one of three accidents caused by Salameh in late 1992 and early in 1993.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] El Sayyid Nosair, one of the blind sheikh's men, was arrested in 1991 for the murder of Rabbi Meir Kahane.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] According to prosecutors, "the Red" Mahmud Abouhalima, also convicted in the bombing, told Wadih el Hage to buy the .357 caliber revolver used by Nosair in the Kahane shooting.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In the initial court case in NYS Criminal Court, Nosair was acquitted of murder but convicted of gun charges (in a related and follow-up case in Federal Court, he was convicted).
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Dozens of Arabic bomb-making manuals and documents related to terrorist plots were found in Nosair's New Jersey apartment, with manuals from Army Special Warfare Center at Fort Bragg, North Carolina, secret memos linked to the Joint Chiefs of Staff, and 1,440 rounds of ammunition.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] According to the transcript of his trial, Yousef hoped that his explosion would topple Tower 1 which would fall into Tower 2, killing the occupants of both buildings, which he estimated to be about 250,000 people in revenge for U.S. support for Israel against Palestine.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] According to journalist Steve Coll, Yousef mailed letters to various New York newspapers just before the attack, in which he claimed he belonged to "Liberation Army, Fifth Battalion".
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Yousef did not make any religious justification for the bombing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] When asked about his religious views, he was evasive.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] On Friday, February 26, 1993, Ramzi Yousef and a Jordanian friend, Eyad Ismoil, drove a yellow Ford Econoline Ryder van into Lower Manhattan, and pulled into the public parking garage beneath the World Trade Center around noon.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] They parked on the underground B-2 level.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Yousef ignited the 20-foot (6.1 m) fuse, and fled.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Twelve minutes later, at 12:18 p.m., the bomb exploded in the underground garage, generating an estimated pressure of 150,000 pounds per square inch (1.0 GPa).
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The bomb opened a 100-foot-wide (30 m) hole through four sublevels of concrete.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The detonation velocity of this bomb was about 15,000 feet per second (10,000 mph; 4.6 km/s).
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The bomb instantly cut off the World Trade Center's main electrical power line, knocking out the emergency lighting system.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The bomb caused smoke to rise to the 93rd floor of both towers, including through the stairwells (which were not pressurized), and smoke went up the damaged elevators in both towers.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] With thick smoke filling the stairwells, evacuation was difficult for building occupants and led to many smoke inhalation injuries.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Hundreds were trapped in elevators in the towers when the power was cut, including a group of 17 kindergartners on their way down from the South Tower observation deck, who were trapped between the 35th and 36th floors for five hours.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Six people were killed: five Port Authority employees, one of whom was pregnant, and a businessman whose car was in the parking garage.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Additionally, over 1,000 people were injured, most during the evacuation that followed the blast.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] A report from the US Fire Administration states that "Among the scores of people who fled to the roofs of the towers, 28 with medical problems were airlifted by New York City police helicopters".
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] It is known that 15 people received traumatic injuries from the blast and 20 complained of cardiac problems.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] One firefighter was hospitalized, while 87 others, 35 police officers, and an EMS worker were also injured in dealing with the fires and other aftermath.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Telephone service for much of Lower Manhattan was also disrupted.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Yousef's plan was that the North Tower would fall onto the South Tower, collapsing them both.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The tower did not collapse, but the garage was severely damaged in the explosion.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Had the van been parked closer to the WTC's poured concrete foundations, Yousef's plan might have succeeded.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Yousef escaped to Pakistan several hours after the bombing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] First reports described the explosion as "having the characteristics of from 200 to 300 pounds of a plastic explosive called Semtex".
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] According to an article published in 1997, Semtex was only used as a detonating charge in the bomb but it is unknown how the terrorists would have obtained Semtex (which is not a "homemade" explosive, unlike other supposed components of the bomb).
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] According to the FBI, Yousef was assisted by Iraqi bomb maker Abdul Rahman Yasin, who helped assemble the complex 1,310-pound (590 kg) bomb, which was made of a urea nitrate main charge with aluminum, magnesium and ferric oxide particles surrounding the explosive.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The charge used nitroglycerine, ammonium nitrate dynamite, smokeless powder and fuse as booster explosives.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Three tanks of bottled hydrogen were also placed in a circular configuration around the main charge, to enhance the fireball and afterburn of the solid metal particles.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The use of compressed gas cylinders in this type of attack closely resembles the 1983 Beirut barracks bombing 10 years earlier.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Both of these attacks used compressed gas cylinders to create fuel-air and thermobaric bombs that release more energy than conventional high explosives.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] According to testimony in the bomb trial, only once before the 1993 attack had the FBI recorded a bomb that used urea nitrate.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The Ryder van used in the bombing had 295 cubic feet (8.4 m3) of space, which would hold up to 2,000 pounds (910 kg) of explosives.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] However, the van was not filled to capacity.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Yousef used four 20-foot-long (6.1 m) fuses, all covered in surgical tubing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Yasin calculated that the fuse would trigger the bomb in twelve minutes after he had used a cigarette lighter to light the fuse.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Yousef wanted the smoke to remain in the tower, smothering people inside, killing them slowly.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] A granite memorial fountain honoring the victims who died during the bombing was designed by Elyn Zimmerman and dedicated on May 25, 1995, on the Austin J.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Tobin Plaza, directly above the site of the explosion.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] It contained the names of the six adults who were killed in the attack, as well as an inscription written both in English and Spanish that read: "On February 26, 1993, a bomb set by terrorists exploded below this site.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] A recovered fragment of the fountain marked "John D", from the name of John DiGiovanni, was later incorporated into a temporary memorial designed by Port Authority architect Jacqueline Hanley, and erected on the Liberty Street side of the site following the September 11 attacks.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The rest of the fountain was never recovered, and any of its remains were removed from Ground Zero along with the rest of the rubble.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] At the 9/11 Memorial, which opened on the tenth anniversary of the 2001 attacks, the people who died in the 1993 bombing are memorialized at the North Pool, on Panel N-73.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The recovered fragment of the memorial fountain is on display among other artifacts related to the bombing inside the museum's historical exhibition.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The *Postcards* memorial in Staten Island contains the name of Stephen Knapp, the sole person from that borough who died in the bombing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Though the cause of the blast was not immediately known, agents and bomb technicians from the ATF, FBI, and the NYPD quickly responded to the scene.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In the days after the bombing, investigators surveyed the damage and looked for clues.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] About 300 FBI agents were deployed under the codename TRADEBOM.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] While combing through the rubble in the underground parking area, Donald Sadowy, Bomb Squad Detective at New York City Police Department, located some internal component fragments from the vehicle that delivered the bomb.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Detective Sadowy was also an automotive specialist, and his efforts led to the discovery of the license plate number as recounted in *Rendered Safe* by Jeff Ingber.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] A vehicle identification number (VIN), found on a piece from an axle, gave investigators crucial information that led them to a Ryder van rented from DIB Leasing in Jersey City.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Here they found the number of the yellow Ford Econoline Ryder van, XA 70668, on an Alabama number plate.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The Ford Econoline had been reported stolen in Jersey City on February 25, one day before the bombing, as per FBI's National Crime Information Center computer.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Investigators determined that the vehicle had been rented by Mohammed A.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Salameh, one of Yousef's co-conspirators.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Salameh had reported the van stolen, and when he returned on March 4, 1993 to get his deposit back, authorities arrested him.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Salameh's arrest led police to the apartment of Abdul Rahman Yasin at 40 Pamrapo Avenue in Jersey City, New Jersey, which Yasin was sharing with his mother, the same building as Ramzi Yousef's apartment.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Yasin was taken to the FBI's Newark field office in Newark, New Jersey, and was then released.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The next day, he flew back to Iraq, via Amman, Jordan.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Yasin was later indicted for the attack, and in 2001 he was placed on the initial list of the FBI Most Wanted Terrorists, on which he remains today.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] He disappeared before the U.S. coalition invasion, Operation Iraqi Freedom, in 2003.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The capture of Salameh and Yasin led authorities to Ramzi Yousef's apartment, where they found bomb-making materials and a business card from Mohammed Jamal Khalifa.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Khalifa was arrested on December 14, 1994, and was deported to Jordan by the INS on May 5, 1995.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] He was acquitted by a Jordanian court and lived as a free man in Saudi Arabia until he was killed in 2007.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In 2002, it was made public that Yasin, the only person involved in the bombing who was never convicted by US authorities, was being held as a prisoner on the outskirts of Baghdad, Iraq since 1994.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] When journalist Lesley Stahl interviewed him there for a segment on *60 Minutes* on May 23, 2002, Yasin appeared in prison pajamas and handcuffs.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Yasin has not been seen or heard from since the interview.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] He was not located during the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In March 1994, Salameh, Nidal Ayyad, Mahmud Abouhalima and Ahmad Ajaj were each convicted in the World Trade Center bombing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In May 1994, they were sentenced to 240 years in prison.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In the years since, they have received several sentencing reductions, which could allow them to walk free in their 90s or 100s.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The South Tower did not reopen for tenants until March 18, 1993, (the World Trade Center Observation Deck reopened on April 17, 1993) while the North Tower remained closed until April 1, 1993.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The cost to repair both buildings was estimated at $250 million.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The Vista International Hotel at 3 World Trade Center remained closed until November 1, 1994, after extensive repairs and renovations that amounted to $65 million.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The concourse level was reopened on March 27, 1993, while the parking garage reopened on September 1, 1993, for some government employee's vehicles.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Commercial tenants' employees were not allowed until spring 1994.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Also, new security measures were introduced including identification tags for approved cars and drivers, surveillance cameras and a barrier rising out of the roadway to stop rogue vehicles.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Even though Windows on the World on the North Tower's 107th floor wasn't damaged, the explosion damaged receiving areas, the air-conditioning system, storage, and parking spots used by the restaurant complex.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] As a result, the restaurant was forced to shut down.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The Port Authority decided to hire Joseph Baum, the restaurant's original designer, to renovate the space at a cost of $25 million.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The restaurant reopened on June 26, 1996 and Cellar in the Sky reopened after Labor Day of that same year.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In the course of the trial, it was revealed that the FBI had an informant, a former Egyptian army officer named Emad Salem.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Salem claimed FBI involvement in building of the bomb.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] He secretly recorded hundreds of hours of telephone conversations with his FBI handlers.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Federal authorities denied Salem's view of events and the *New York Times* concluded that the tapes "do not make clear the extent to which Federal authorities knew that there was a plan to bomb the World Trade Center, merely that they knew that a bombing of some sort was being discussed".
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Although the FBI received the credit, Diplomatic Security Service (DSS) special agents actually found and arrested Ramzi Yousef, the architect of the 1993 World Trade Center bombing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Special Agents Bill Miller and Jeff Riner were given a tip by an associate of Ramzi Yousef about his location.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In coordination with the Pakistani Inter-Services Intelligence (ISI), DSS arrested Ramzi Yousef.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In October 2001 in a PBS interview, former CIA Director James Woolsey claimed that Ramzi Yousef worked for Iraqi intelligence.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] He suggested the grand jury investigation turned up evidence pointing to Iraq that the Justice Department "brushed aside".
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] But Neil Herman, who headed the FBI investigation, noted "The one glaring connection that can't be overlooked is Yasin.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] We pursued that on every level, traced him to a relative and a location, and we made overtures to get him back." However, Herman says that Yasin's presence in Baghdad does not mean Iraq sponsored the attack: "We looked at that rather extensively.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] There were no ties to the Iraqi government." CNN terrorism reporter Peter L.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Bergen writes, "In sum, by the mid-'90s, the Joint Terrorism Task Force in New York, the F.B.I., the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Claims of direct Iraqi involvement come from Dr.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Laurie Mylroie of the American Enterprise Institute and former associate professor of the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Naval War College, with the claims rejected by others.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In March 2008, the Pentagon released its study of some 600,000 documents captured in Iraq after the 2003 invasion (see 2008 Pentagon Report).
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In the wake of the bombing and the chaotic evacuation which followed, the World Trade Center and many of the firms inside of it revamped emergency procedures, particularly with regard to evacuation of the towers.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The New York Port Authority was to govern as the main security for the World Trade Center buildings.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] All packages were scanned at various checkpoints then sent up to the proper addressee.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] These policies played a role in evacuating the building during the September 11 attacks, which destroyed the towers.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Free access to the roofs, which had enabled evacuation by police helicopter in the 1993 bombing, was ended soon after.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] , attempted to alert high-ranking U.S. government officials of a future terrorist attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] While victims' family members and injured survivors of the 2001 terrorist attack received compensation from the September 11th Victim Compensation Fund, no such compensation was given to those affected by the 1993 bombing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Some of the victims (which included families of the killed victims) of the 1993 World Trade Center bombings sued the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey for damages.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] A decision was handed down in 2005, assigning liability for the bombings to the Port Authority.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] The decision declared that the agency was 68 percent responsible for the bombing, and the terrorists bore only 32 percent of the responsibility.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] In January 2008, the Port Authority asked a five-judge panel of the Appellate Division of the New York State Supreme Court in Manhattan to throw out the decision, describing the jury's verdict as "bizarre".
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] On April 29, 2008, a New York State Appeals Court unanimously upheld the jury's verdict.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Under New York law, a defendant who is more than 50 percent at fault can be held fully financially liable.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] On September 22, 2011, the New York Court of Appeals, in a four to three ruling, excluded the Port Authority from claims of negligence related to the 1993 bombing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] It has been argued that the problem with the apportionment of responsibility in the case is not the jury's verdict, but rather New York's tort-reform-produced state apportionment law.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] Traditionally, courts do not compare intentional and negligent fault.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] *The Restatement Third of Torts: Apportionment of Liability* recommends a rule to prevent juries from having to make comparisons like the terrorist–Port Authority comparison in this case.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1993-world-trade-center-bombing] However, if a jurisdiction does compare these intentional and negligent torts, courts' second-best position is to do what the NYS Appeals Court did—to uphold all jury apportionments, even those that assign greater, or perhaps far greater, responsibility to negligent than intentional parties.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] The **1998 Bank of America robbery** was a bank robbery of $1.6 million in cash at the Bank of America in the World Trade Center's North Tower, in New York City, on January 14, 1998.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] The robbery was plotted and executed by Ralph Guarino, an actor and petty criminal with connections to the DeCavalcante crime family.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] Guarino received some intelligence from a WTC worker named Salvatore Calciano, who told him about the increased security that followed the 1993 World Trade Center bombing and would later give him his employee ID badge from a friend of Calciano.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] He also told Guarino when a Brink's armored truck would arrive to deliver money via elevator to the 11th floor of the North Tower (Tower One) of the WTC.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] The two of them planned the robbery and recruited three other criminals to complete the actual robbery: Richie Gillette, 39, from Windsor Terrace, Brooklyn, as well as his friends Melvin Folk, 44, and Mike Reed, 34.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] On Wednesday, January 14, 1998, a Brink's van pulled up to the World Trade Center at around 8:30 a.m. and began unloading bags of money.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] Only Gillette wore a ski mask in order to make it more difficult for others to identify him.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] They successfully subdued the WTC employees and guards, and proceeded to steal the bags.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] They took a total of $1.6 million (worth $3.2 million today) and exited the WTC at 8:45 a.m.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] In the aftermath of the robbery, Folk and Reed returned to their old neighborhoods and were quickly identified and captured.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] Gillette was questioned by security after boarding an Amtrak train but was not detained at the time.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] He was later found and arrested in Albuquerque, New Mexico, two days later, at 8:30 pm, January 16.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] The FBI did not believe the three had acted alone and began to search for a mastermind.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] Guarino had various ideas of how to get rid of the money but ultimately was unable to follow through on any plans before FBI agents came to arrest him at his Staten Island home.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-bank-of-america-robbery] Following his arrest, Guarino agreed to become an FBI informant on the DeCavalcante crime family.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] The **1998 United States embassy bombings** were a series of attacks that occurred on August 7, 1998.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] More than 220 people were killed in two nearly simultaneous truck bomb explosions in two East African capital cities, one at the United States embassy in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, and the other at the United States embassy in Nairobi, Kenya.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Fazul Abdullah Mohammed and Abdullah Ahmed Abdullah were deemed responsible with planning and orchestrating the bombings.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] In retaliation for the bombings, U.S. president Bill Clinton ordered Operation Infinite Reach on August 20, 1998.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Many American sources concluded that the bombings were intended as revenge for United States involvement in the extradition and alleged torture of four members of Egyptian Islamic Jihad (EIJ) who had been arrested in Albania in the two months prior to the attacks for a series of murders in Egypt.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] The following month, a communique was issued warning the United States that a "response" was being prepared to "repay" them for their interference.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] However, the *9/11 Commission Report* claims that preparations began shortly after Osama bin Laden issued his February 1998 fatwa.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] According to journalist Lawrence Wright, the Nairobi operation was named after the Kaaba in Mecca; the Dar es Salaam bombing was called Operation al-Aqsa in Jerusalem, but "neither had an obvious connection to the American embassies in Africa.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Bin Laden initially said that the sites had been targeted because of the 'invasion' of Somalia; then he described an American plan to partition Sudan, which he said was hatched in the embassy in Nairobi.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] In the second half of 1999, bin Laden spoke to a crowd of graduates from a training camp in Afghanistan about the attacks and explained the reasons for targeting the Nairobi embassy.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Bin Laden said Operation Restore Hope in Somalia was directed from the Nairobi embassy and claimed the lives of 30,000 Muslims, the Southern Sudanese rebel leader John Garang was supported from there and it was the largest American Intelligence center in East Africa.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] In May 1998, a villa in Nairobi was purchased by one of the bombers to enable a bomb to be built in the garage.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Sheikh Ahmed Salim Swedan purchased a beige Toyota Dyna truck in Nairobi and a 1987 Nissan Atlas refrigeration truck in Dar es Salaam.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Six metal bars were used to form a "cage" on the back of the Atlas to accommodate the bomb.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] In June 1998, KK Mohamed rented House 213 in the Illala district of Dar es Salaam, about four miles (six kilometers) from the U.S. embassy.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] A white Suzuki Samurai was used to haul bomb components, hidden in rice sacks, to House 213.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] In both Nairobi and Dar es Salaam, Mohammed Odeh supervised construction of two very large 2,000-pound (900 kg) destructive devices.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] The Nairobi bomb was made of 400 to 500 cylinders of TNT (about the size of drink cans), ammonium nitrate, aluminum powder, and detonating cord.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] The explosives were packed into twenty specially designed wooden crates that were sealed and then placed in the bed of the trucks.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Muhsin Musa Matwalli Atwah ran a wire from the bomb to a set of batteries in the back of the truck cab and then to a detonator switch beneath the dashboard.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] The Dar es Salaam bomb was of slightly different construction: the TNT was attached to fifteen oxygen tanks and gas canisters and was surrounded with four bags of ammonium nitrate fertilizer and some sandbags to tamp and direct the blast.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] The bombings were scheduled for August 7, the eighth anniversary of the arrival of U.S. troops in Saudi Arabia during the early stages of the Persian Gulf War, likely a choice by bin Laden.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] When bin Laden's bodyguard asked him after the attacks whether so many victims were really necessary, he replied referring to al-Qaeda's 1996 and 1998 *fatwas* declaring war on America and Israel: "We warned the whole world what would happen to the friends of America.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] EDT), suicide bombers in trucks loaded with explosives parked outside the embassies in Dar es Salaam and Nairobi, and almost simultaneously detonated.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] A total of 213 people were killed in the Nairobi blast, while 11 were killed in Dar es Salaam.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] An estimated 4,000 in Nairobi were wounded, and another 85 in Dar es Salaam.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Seismological readings analyzed after the bombs indicated energy of between 3 and 17 short tons (3 and 15 metric tons) of high-explosive material.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Although the attacks were directed at U.S. facilities, the vast majority of casualties were local citizens of the two African countries.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Twelve Americans were killed, including two Central Intelligence Agency employees in the Nairobi embassy, Tom Shah (aka Uttamlal Thomas Shah) and Molly Huckaby Hardy.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Marine Sergeant Jesse "Nathan" Aliganga, a Marine Security Guard at the Nairobi embassy, and U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Army Staff Sergeant Kenneth Ray Hobson II were also killed in the attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] While Jihad Mohammed Ali, 24, alias 'Azzam' drove the Toyota Dyna quickly toward the Nairobi embassy along with Mohamed Rashed Daoud Al-Owhali, local security guard Benson Okuku Bwaku was warned to open the gate immediately and fired upon when he refused to comply.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Al-Owhali threw a stun grenade at embassy guards before exiting the vehicle and running off.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Osama bin Laden later offered the explanation that it had been Al-Owhali's intention to leap out and shoot the guards to clear a path for the truck, but that he had left his pistol in the truck and subsequently ran off.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] As Bwaku radioed to Marine Post One for backup, the truck detonated.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] The explosion damaged the embassy building and collapsed the neighboring Ufundi Building where most victims were killed, mainly students and staff of a secretarial college housed there.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] The heat from the blast was channeled between the buildings towards Haile Selassie Avenue where a packed commuter bus was burned.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Windows were shattered in a radius of nearly 1⁄2 mi (800 meters).
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] A large number of eye injuries occurred because people in buildings nearby who had heard the first explosion of the hand grenade and the shooting went to their office windows to have a look when the main blast occurred and shattered the windows.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Meanwhile, the Atlas truck that attacked the U.S.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Embassy at 36 Laibon Road, Dar es Salaam was being driven by Hamden Khalif Allah Awad, known as "Ahmed the German" due to his blond hair, a former camp trainer who had arrived in the country only a few days earlier.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] The death toll was less than in Nairobi as the U.S. embassy was located outside the city center in the upscale Oysterbay neighborhood, and a water truck prevented the suicide bombers from getting closer to the structure.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Following the attacks, a group calling itself the "Liberation Army for Holy Sites" took credit for the bombings.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] U.S. investigators believe the term was a cover used by Egyptian Islamic Jihad, who had actually perpetrated the bombing.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] In response to the bombings, President Bill Clinton ordered Operation Infinite Reach, a series of cruise missile strikes on targets in Sudan and Afghanistan on August 20, 1998, announcing the planned strike in a prime-time address on U.S. television.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] The United Nations Security Council passed Resolution 1189 condemning the attacks on the embassies.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Both embassies were heavily damaged and the Nairobi embassy had to be rebuilt.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] It is now located across the road from the United Nations Office at Nairobi for security purposes.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] A memorial park was constructed on the former embassy site, dedicated on the third anniversary of the attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Public protest marred the opening ceremony after it was announced that the park, including its wall inscribed with the names of the dead, would not be free to the public.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Within months following the bombings, the United States Department of State Bureau of Diplomatic Security added Kenya to its Antiterrorism Assistance Program (ATA), which was originally created in 1983.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] While the addition was largely a formality to reaffirm U.S. commitment to fighting terrorism in Kenya, it nonetheless sparked the beginning of an active bilateral antiterrorism campaign by the United States and Kenya.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] The U.S. government also rapidly and permanently increased the monetary aid to Kenya.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Immediate changes included a $42 million grant targeted specifically towards Kenyan victims.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] In 2001, James Owens and others filed a civil lawsuit against Sudan for its role in the attack under the Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act with the recently added 1996 amendments for state-sponsored terrorism.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] They argued that Sudan was at fault for providing sanctuary to the bombers prior to the attack.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Congress amended the Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act in 2008 to correct this and to allow its provisions to retroactively apply to existing lawsuits, including Owens' case.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] With that, hundreds more plaintiffs joined the suit, eventually with more than 700 parties listed.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] By 2014, the district court awarded the plaintiffs over $10 billion.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Sudan, which had not appeared during the initial lawsuit, appealed the judgment, arguing it did not understand the US civil suit system and did not understand the consequences of not appearing, but also challenged the retroactive nature of the 2008 change to the Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] The appeals court discounted Sudan's argument regarding its lack of understanding, and upheld the lower court's finding that Sudan was liable for the bombings, but ruled that the $4.3 billion of punitive damages could not be applied retroactively.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] The plaintiffs petitioned to the Supreme Court to appeal, and in May 2020, the Court ruled in *Opati v.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Republic of Sudan* that the punitive damages could be retroactively applied, restoring the $4.3 billion that had been awarded at the District Court.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] In October 2020, President Donald Trump announced that the United States would remove Sudan from the State Sponsors of Terrorism list, after they had agreed to pay $335 million in compensation to the families of victims of the embassy bombings.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] Following the investigation, an indictment was issued.
[src:1993-world-trade-center-bombing/1998-united-states-embassy-bombings] It charges the following 21 people for various alleged roles in the bombings.
